Under the pressure of these diffi- culties, combined with the necessity of military service, they fell into the power of the capitalists‚ from whom they were obliged to borrow, and under the severe Roman law of debt became in most cases slaves or at least serfs of their creditors. In other worda the farmer and yeoman classes of Rome were beginning to be transformed into a class of villeins.

Under these circumstances, it is clear that the only chance of salvation for the state lay in the plebeians discovering in time their real power, and extorting political recognition from the patricians. That power lay in the simple fact that the patricians could not do without them. They formed numerically far the largcr portion of the community, and they furnished the bulk of the Roman armies.
